The real Long March
Every nation has its founding myth.
For communist China, it is the Long March – a story that parallels the Exodus of the Israelites led by Moses.
I grew up with this.
The myth is quickly told.
The young Communist Party and its three Red Armies were driven out of their bases in the south by Chiang Kai-shek's nationalist government at the beginning of the 1930s.
Chased and persecuted by their enemies, they crossed high mountains, raging rivers, and rugged pastures, with Mao steering the march from victory to victory.
After two years and 16,000 kilometers of steadfastness, courage, and hope, the Red Armies reached Northwestern China despite incredibly poor prospects.
Only one-fifth of the 200,000 soldiers remained – exhausted, severely wounded, but full of defiance.
A decade later, they struck back, defeated Chiang Kai-shek, and established Mao's New China.
To what extent does communist China's founding myth hold up to reality?
In 2004, seventy years after the start of the Long March, I set out to follow its trail.
It is still a frightening journey through regions that have changed little to this day, inaccessible and incredibly impoverished.
Of the 40,000 survivors, perhaps only 500 are still alive today. I located 40 of them and spoke with them – they were ordinary people who were left behind or managed to survive until the end, but their stories were extremely enlightening.
Huan Zhiji was barely taller than his rifle when he joined the Red Army.
He had no choice: His father had been arrested and was not released until Huang agreed.
He thought of fleeing the flag, but stayed, fearing being caught and shot.
Many fled.
Six weeks into the march, Mao's First Army had shrunk from 86,000 to 30,000 soldiers.
The blame for this loss is still attributed to the Battle of the Xiang River, the first major engagement of the army during the Long March.
But at most 15,000 died in the battle, the rest disappeared.
Another battle, at the Dadu River, is at the heart of the Long March legend. Allegedly, 22 brave men overwhelmed a regiment of nationalist troops guarding the chain-link bridge at Luding with machine guns, clearing the way for the marchers.
Mao told Edgar Snow, the author of Red Star Over China, that crossing the Dadu River was the most significant event of the entire Long March, and it is thus revered as such today.
However, documents I have reviewed suggest that the general who led the division across the Dadu initially told party historians a completely different story. "The matter wasn't as complicated as people later portrayed it," he said. "When examining historical facts, one should pay attention to the truth.
"How it is portrayed is another matter."
So the legend lives on.
Over the Dadu, there was merely a skirmish.
The local warlord, who hated Chiang Kai-shek, let Mao pass.
As a reward, he later received a ministerial position in the communist government.
The march participants did not know where they were heading.
There were constant discussions about the final destination.
When they met in North China in October 1936, this was celebrated as the end of the march.
But the "promised land" was not as promised.
It could barely feed its own population, let alone the Red Army.
The soldiers had no clothing to protect themselves from the icy cold.
The women were ordered to turn around and go home because there was not enough food.
Just over a month after the merger of the three Red Armies, the party decided that the Long March must continue.
But it was saved by the capture of Chiang Kai-shek by the general Chiang had assigned to destroy the Communists.
As part of the price for his release, Chiang acknowledged the Communists as legitimate.
The Long March was concluded.
Not for the 21,000 men and women of the Western Legion.
They belonged to the Fourth Army, led by Zhang Guotao, Mao's arch-rival, and had the mission to seek help from Russia across the western Chinese border.
However, Mao gave them contradictory orders, so they could neither fight nor retreat.
Trapped on barren land where survival was difficult, they were eradicated by the superior forces of the Muslim warlords.
Only 400 reached the border, the rest were killed or captured.
It was the greatest defeat of the Red Army.
Nevertheless, it is missing from the official historical narrative.
A Muslim commander took Wang Quanyan, the commanding officer, as his mistress.
This was enough to make her a traitor in the eyes of the party and to deny all the years she had devoted to the army.
They and the other survivors of the Fourth Army had to fight for half a century to be recognized as participants in the march.
The participants of the Long March were resolute, fought, starved, despairing, and persevered.
The hunger drove the soldiers to take hostages to extort ransom money.
The liquidations continued until practically no officers were left to take command in the battles.
If the marchers had doubts, they overcame them with the help of communist propaganda.
They bore their martyrdom with a courage and self-sacrifice unmatched in the history of China and other nations.
The participants of the Long March were resolute, fought, starved, despaired, and persevered.
What drove them to do this?
I questioned one of the top generals what he knew about communism back then. "I didn't know then any more than I do today," he replied. "In fact, I doubt even Mao himself really knew what it was." For him, who had survived extreme poverty and oppression, communism was a beautiful dream that kept him alive and gave him hope for a just and progressive society.
No one perhaps – or could – know how much suffering was still to come, how great the sacrifice, and how enormous the difference between dream and reality would be.
